  "doc_id": "28060",
  "text": "Two viral diseases of lagomorphs, myxomatosis since the 1950s and rabbit haemorrhagic disease since the 1990s, have caused a severe decline in rabbit numbers throughout continental Western Europe. Among the causes of the problem are translocations of domestic rabbits and voluntary or involuntary transmission of the virus to wild rabbits [CITATION_1] . The combined effects of these diseases, probably exacerbated by hunting, have contributed largely to the adverse situation of many rabbit predators, such as the Iberian lynx and many raptors [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ). This is probably one of the best examples of the huge effect that shared wildlife diseases can have on conservation and on management.",
